-- PRESS DIGEST-Hong Kong - July 9
-- By Yimou Lee
-- Tue Jul 08, 2014 10:08PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, July 9 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Wednesday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST -- "Unexpected shocks" like the planned Occupy Central protest could trigger a property market slump, leading international bank Barclays warned. (http://bit.ly/VHgJKJ) -- Home-grown mainland consumer brands could be ready to compete on the world stage by 2017 and Li & Fung Ltd <0494.HK> spinoff Global Brands wants to be the one taking them there, according to Chief Executive Bruce Rockowitz. (http://bit.ly/1surmex) -- Hong Kong financial institutions that failed to register for the Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act by the July 1 deadline risk suffering not only U.S. penalties but also penalties for violating Hong Kong regulations, which may include losing their licences, said Sharon Lam, a partner at Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu. (http://bit.ly/1suraMs) -- Shares of Wing Hang Bank Ltd <0302.HK>, which is being taken over by Oversea-Chinese Banking Corp Ltd's <OCBC.SI>, could fall as much as 40 percent if OCBC did not garner enough stock to delist the company, Credit Suisse Group said. THE STANDARD -- Macau is facing threats to its growth from the slowing mainland economy and greater foreign competition, escalating the need for the world's largest gambling hub to diversify from its casino gaming roots, said Pansy Ho Chiu-king, who co-heads MGM China Holdings <2282.HK>. (http://bit.ly/1qIpC1Z) -- HSBC <0005.HK> has been criticised for modifying its research comments just a day after downgrading its investment rating for Hong Kong solely over Occupy Central concerns. (http://bit.ly/VWp4ul) -- Hong Kong's fund management hit a record high for a second consecutive year of HK$16 trillion in 2013, up 27.2 percent. But the growth rate was slower than the 39.3 percent seen in 2012, a Securities and Futures Commission survey showed. (http://bit.ly/1kBPbMr)  ORIENTAL DAILY NEWS -- A representative of a U.S. trade union has submitted a request to the Macau government, asking for information regarding the commitment of land rights in Cotai to Wynn Macau Ltd <1128.HK>, which paid $50 million to Tien Chiao Entertainment and Investment Co in order for Wynn to develop its own resort casino on the land.HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- Hong Kong Stock Exchange and Clearing Ltd <0388.HK> is teaming up with Singapore Exchange Ltd <SGXL.SI> to establish "Liquidity Hub" in Hong Kong, which allows agencies in the Greater China area to directly participate in futures trading in Singapore.